<p>Itâ€™s unclear if Gasol can sustain his peak-performance on both ends of the floor over a full season. Thatâ€™s not a diss, or a suggestion his health may begin tapering off as he turns 30, but me looking at his career stats. For three-consecutive seasons his per-game counting stats have plateaued; his 12 FGA in 2013-14 were a career-high â€” andÂ that mark just feels too low. The team simply plays at a higher level when he is shooting and hitting the 10-14 foot jumper at league-high rates. His ability to create offense with the pass separates him even further from his peers, and while Conley is among the most underrated guards in the NBA, Memphis desperately relies on Gasolâ€™s knack for creating offense out of the high post and atÂ the nail.</p>

<p>Considering that Randolph/Allen arenâ€™t getting any younger, and Gasol is a free agentÂ at seasonâ€™s end, this is probably Memphisâ€™ last chance to make a real run in the West; its conference finals appearance in 2013 will always be prefaced with Westbrookâ€™s injury and the subsequent shellacking it received by the Spurs. Memphis matches up terribly with San Antonio but interestingly enough they match up great against everyone else. They also have NO FEAR of Oklahoma City or the Clippers. Any playoff bracket whereÂ Memphis can avoid San Antonio in 2014-15 could spell trouble for the rest of the West.</p>

<p>In 2013, <a href="http://grantland.com/features/memphis-grizzlies-center-marc-gasol-most-overlooked-big-man-nba-maybe-best/">Gasol told Grantlandâ€™s Jordon Ritter Conn</a> that when he submitted his name for the NBA draft at age 22 he refused to come to the United States and work out for teams. â€œI didnâ€™t care about the draft,â€ he says. â€œI didnâ€™t want to do the workouts â€” they put you in two-on-two full-court drills with guards. Thatâ€™s not going to help me. I thought if someone wants to see who I am and how I play, they have to come here. Thatâ€™s not being cocky. You just have to see me in five-on-five, in a real game, to understand.â€</p>

