<p>Very few players affect each basketball game as much as Gasol does, something that manifested itself into the 2012-13 Defensive POY award despite him not being an elite shot-blocker. Team Spain losing before it could play Team USA was a huge let down for many reasons butÂ possibly the largest reason was that we couldnâ€™t see Gasol take on the American-born players. There would have been something really interesting about seeing if his impact on both ends could chip away at the supreme athleticism â€” albeit, a JV version â€” of Team USA.</p>

<p>He might not be the worldâ€™s greatest athlete but he overcomes any purely physicalÂ shortcomings with the methodology of an accomplished chess player.Â There is a gravity to Gasolâ€™s game, as his teammates, four at a time, seem better off having him to play with.</p>

<p>We, meaning basketball fans and writers, talk about the best basketball players in the world all the time. The list starts with LeBron James and Kevin Durant, and then it moves to the Chris Pauls and Blake Griffins, the Stephen Currys and Dirk Nowitzkis and Carmelo Anthonys. These are all great players. Marc Gasol doesnâ€™t really get put up on that list, though. Maybe itâ€™s because he has yet to show a true aggression for creating offense at an elite level, and maybe itâ€™s because his teams have lost their fair share of first round series. Maybe everyone is waiting for Grit and Grind to make a run at the NBA Finals before putting Marc Gasol on that list.</p>

<p>Iâ€™m just having a harder and harder time believing that Gasol isnâ€™t one of the best basketball players in the NBA, period.</p>
